nage-ads-on-membership-sites/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 19 Jun 2017 13:22:11 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"Paid Memberships Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=65348";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:551:"<p>Closed community- and membership areas are a proven way to share your content with a chosen audience. With Advanced Ads Pro you can simply manage your ads on those membership sites as well as target your ads in relation to the membership level of your visitors. In this tutorial you will learn: How to set [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-ads-on-membership-sites/">How to manage ads on membership sites</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Joachim";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10644:"<p>Closed community- and membership areas are a proven way to share your content with a chosen audience. With <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> you can simply manage your ads on those membership sites as well as target your ads in relation to the membership level of your visitors.</p>\n<p><strong>In this tutorial you will learn:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>How to set up a membership site</li>\n<li>How to manage ads on closed membership areas</li>\n<li>How to target users with different membership levels</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>How to set up a membership site</h2>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/paid-memberships-pro-checkbox.png"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-65359" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/paid-memberships-pro-checkbox.png" alt="" width="291" height="247" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/paid-memberships-pro-checkbox.png 291w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/paid-memberships-pro-checkbox-60x51.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/paid-memberships-pro-checkbox-150x127.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 291px) 100vw, 291px" /></a>One of the most popular solutions to create membership areas on a WordPress is the free plugin <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/paid-memberships-pro/">Paid Memberships Pro</a>. Advanced Ads Pro automatically integrates with this plugin.</p>\n<p>The first steps with Paid Memberships Pro are quite easy. After the plugin is activated, you can define different membership levels. They will allow you to enable or disable the access to content, which is tagged for specific membership levels.</p>\n<p>The example on the image shows three different membership levels: „Free“, „Supporter“ und „Premium Membership“.</p>\n<p>The membership plugin adds a checkbox to the edit screen of content like categories, pages or posts. Using them, you can define the specific membership level necessary to access it. Unregistered users or those with insufficient memberships will see a corresponding note instead of the content.</p>\n<h2>How to manage ads on closed membership areas</h2>\n<p>With Advanced Ads Pro you can use the display condition „PMP Page Level“ to show or hide ads on membership sites. After you selected the condition you can choose the available membership levels from a list. Doing so, you can define exactly whether ads should be displayed on sites which require a specific membership level or not.</p>\n<h3>Example 1: How to deactivate ads on membership sites</h3>\n<p>Use the following setting to hide ads for all visitors on all sites of a closed membership area.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-65355 size-large" title="Hide all ads on membership sites" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads-679x204.png" alt="Display condition for Paid Memberships Pro" width="679" height="204" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads-679x204.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads-300x90.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads-60x18.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads-150x45.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membership-display-condition-Advanced-Ads.png 700w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Example 2: Display an ad only on specific pages of a membership area</h3>\n<p>Let&#8217;s stay with our previous example but now, we want to hide the same ad on sites which require the memberships „Supporter“ and „Premium“. Furthermore, we are going to display it on all sites of the membership area which require the „Free Membership“. To achieve this, just select those page types from the list on which you want to show the ad.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-65354 size-large" title="Display Condition for Advanced Ads to manage ads on membership sites" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro-679x210.png" alt="Manage ads in Paid Memberships Pro" width="679" height="210" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro-679x210.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro-300x93.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro-60x19.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro-150x47.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/display-condition-paid-memberships-pro.png 700w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<h2>How to target users with different membership levels</h2>\n<p>Paid Memberships Pro adds a new role to all registered users If you use the visitor condition “PMP User Level“ Advanced Ads will identify this user role and can show or hide an ad depending on the visitor’s membership level.</p>\n<h3>Example 3: Hide all ads for registered users</h3>\n<p>You can use the visitor condition “PMP User Level“ to hide ads for users with a registered membership level on those pages that don&#8217;t require any memberships with the following configuration.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-65356 size-large" title="Advanced Ads provides a visitor condition to control ads on membership sites" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-679x276.png" alt="Visitor Condition to manage ads on membership sites" width="679" height="276" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-679x276.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-300x122.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-60x24.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-150x61.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads.png 700w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Example 4: Hide ads for specific memberships</h3>\n<p>To hide ads from specific user groups (these are in our example „Support“ and „Premium Membership“) but to show them to other members you need to select the corresponding user levels like following.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-65357 size-large" title="Visitor Condition of Advanced Ads to control ads on membership sites" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2-679x268.png" alt="ads on WordPress sites with membership" width="679" height="268" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2-679x268.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2-300x118.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2-60x24.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2-150x59.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example2.png 700w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Example 5: Display ads for specific memberships</h3>\n<p>Of course it is possible to reverse this scenario and to display targeted ads to specific user groups. A use case for this setting could be an offer to free registered users to upgrade their memberships.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-65358 size-large" title="Targeted ads to specific user groups on membership sites" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3-679x276.png" alt="Display targeted ads to specific user groups on membership sites" width="679" height="276" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3-679x276.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3-300x122.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3-60x24.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3-150x61.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/membershipvisitor-condition-Advanced-Ads-example3.png 700w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<h2>Issues and limitations</h2>\n<p>Ad management on closed areas of membership sites is currently just working if those sites are created and administrated with the free plugin Paid Memberships Pro. Other membership plugins are currently not supported with a specific display or visitor conditions by Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The different user levels of Paid Memberships Pro are not hierarchically structured. Therefore you’ll need to consider all different membership levels in your ad configurations.</p>\n<p>If you want to use the visitor condition &#8220;PMP User Level&#8221; on WordPress installations where you also run a caching solution, you will need to activate the cache busting feature in <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> to make it work reliably.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-ads-on-membership-sites/">How to manage ads on membership sites</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"How to stop AdSense ads appearing in random positions (QuickStart)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-in-random-positions-quickstart/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 08 Jun 2017 10:50:21 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=65838";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:467:"<p>Do ads seem to appear randomly on your website? If you are using AdSense then this is probably caused by their new QuickStart feature. Find out more about that and how to fix it in this article.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-in-random-positions-quickstart/">How to stop AdSense ads appearing in random positions (QuickStart)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4665:"<p>In the last weeks we received many emails from users reporting AdSense ads appearing randomly on their sites. Some even disabled Advanced Ads and still saw those ads. Either way, in all cases the irritation was not caused Advanced Ads, but a major change in AdSense. However, there is something we did about this anyway.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_66518" style="width: 315px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="size-full wp-image-66518" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/adsense-quickstart-hint.png" alt="AdSense QuickStart warning by Advanced Ads" width="315" height="325" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/adsense-quickstart-hint.png 315w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/adsense-quickstart-hint-291x300.png 291w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/adsense-quickstart-hint-58x60.png 58w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/adsense-quickstart-hint-145x150.png 145w" sizes="(max-width: 315px) 100vw, 315px" /><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">The blue message was added by Advanced Ads to inform ad managers about automatically placed ads on your site.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Automatic ads with QuickStart</h2>\n<p>In early 2017, AdSense introduced <em>QuickStart</em>, a feature that placed AdSense ads automatically on websites. This move should have made the job of webmasters much easier, but caused a lot of confusion when ads appear in less optimized positions.</p>\n<p>For new AdSense accounts, <strong>QuickStart is enabled by default</strong> and since it is placed through the verification ad tag, which is also identical to the page level ad tag, it is easy to bring this to your website without knowing.</p>\n<p>While it is yet too early to say whether this feature is a benefit for publishers or a manual optimization of ad positions works better, using both options will only cause problems, since there might be too many ads on your site.</p>\n<p>Personally, we believe that placing the ads manually is a better basis for optimizing them, especially when you can <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/">split test for positions</a>.</p>\n<h2>QuickStart warning in Advanced Ads</h2>\n<p>In version 1.7.26 of Advanced Ads we added a warning above all ads placed automatically with QuickStart – see image on top of this article. This warning is <strong>only visible to logged in ad managers</strong>!</p>\n<p>In our experience, users who install and run Advanced Ads normally intend to control the position of their ads and running QuickStart ads and your own positions can cause conflicts.</p>\n<p>However, if you feel irritated by this warning, then please <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/support/">let us know</a> and we will add an option to remove it.</p>\n<h2>How to disable QuickStart?</h2>\n<p>In case you don’t want to see these ads on your site, you have different methods to remove them.</p>\n<h3>Disable the QuickStart option</h3>\n<p>You could just go to your AdSense account and search for <em>My Ads &gt; Page-level ads</em> in the main menu. When QuickStart is available for your account then you will find the appropriate option there and can disable it.</p>\n<p>There could be a short delay until the ads no longer appear.</p>\n<h3>Remove the ad code</h3>\n<p>Whether you still have the AdSense verification code enabled or you placed the Page-level ads code into the header of your site, since they are identical, you could remove it in order to also remove QuickStart.</p>\n<p>When you added this code with Advanced Ads then just go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; AdSense</em> and disable the <em>Activate Page-Level ads</em> option.</p>\n<p>This would also remove Page-level ads from your site, if you use them. Manually placed ad units are of course still going to work.</p>\n<p>If ads still appear then please flush the cache of your website, if you are using one, and make sure the AdSense verification tag or Page-level ads code was not placed with another method, e.g. directly into your theme, through a theme option or another plugin.</p>\n<h2>What else?</h2>\n<p>Established accounts should not even see the QuickStart feature. If there are still AdSense ads in random placements and you are using Advanced Ads then please <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/support/">reach out to us for help</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-in-random-positions-quickstart/">How to stop AdSense ads appearing in random positions (QuickStart)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"Insert Ads between Posts in WordPress – 3 different methods";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"https://wpadvancedads.com/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 18 May 2017 13:15:48 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=63255";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:365:"<p>How to insert ads between posts in WordPress with three methods provided by the Advanced Ads plugin.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress/">Insert Ads between Posts in WordPress – 3 different methods</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5445:"<p>While inserting ads in the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/post-ad-injection-placement/">post content</a> is fairly easy, to insert ads between posts on your homepage, category pages or other archives is a bit more complicated. Advanced Ads has a couple of options to do that manually or automatically. This tutorial shows the simplest solutions our ad plugin for WordPress can current provide.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>using a PHP function</li>\n<li>with the Post Lists placement</li>\n<li>with the Custom Positions placement</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Please find the explanation of each method below.</p>\n<h2>Insert ads between posts manually in your template</h2>\n<p>With the basic version of Advanced Ads, you can create a <em>Manual Placement</em> and put it into the loop in template files like <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">home.php</pre> or <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">index.php</pre>. The function to go with is <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">the_ad_placement(''your-placement-id'')</pre> .</p>\n<p>If you want to show the ad only between specific posts (e.g. the fourth and the fifth), you can use the code from below.</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">// global $wp_query; // uncomment if loop content is in another file or function\r\nif( function_exists(''the_ad_placement'') &amp;&amp; $wp_query-&gt;current_post === 4 ){ \r\n    the_ad_placement(''your-placement-id'');\r\n}</pre><p>\n<em>your-placement-id</em> is the id of the placement you created. You get this by clicking on the <em>Usage</em> link in the placement table.</p>\n<p>Please make sure that you have access to your files via FTP and make a backup of the edited file, because a simple PHP error could break your site.</p>\n<p>If coding is not your strength then insert ads between posts with the Post Lists placement, which is explained below.</p>\n<h2>Inserting ads betwen posts automatically (most simple solution)</h2>\n<p>The most simple solution is to use the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placement-post-lists/">Post Lists</a> placement. This is a placement we developed specifically to insert ads between posts. It works similar to the normal content injection.</p>\n<p>The Post Lists placement comes with <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> and can be found under <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em>. A simple setup might look like this:</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-63256 size-full" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example.png" alt="Post Lists placement setup" width="847" height="141" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example.png 847w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example-300x50.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example-679x113.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example-60x10.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/post-list-example-150x25.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 847px) 100vw, 847px" /></a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>This placement is using WordPress standards. You can find more details about it on <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placement-post-lists/">this page</a>.</p>\n<p>If your post list is not based on the default loop or has some specific design then take a look at the Custom Position option below.</p>\n<h2>Using Custom Positions for advanced layouts</h2>\n<p>Some themes have specific layouts for all or some archive pages. This might be a grid on the homepage or an implementation of the post list that is not based on WordPress standards.</p>\n<p>In these situations, the <em>Custom Positions</em> placement might work better than <em>Post Lists</em> to insert ads between posts.</p>\n<p>The Custom Position is a placement that allows you to select any position for an ad. Hence, you can also choose a position between posts on your homepage or other archive pages.</p>\n<p>The example below shows the Custom Position settings after choosing the fourth element in a post list in the frontend.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-68655 size-full" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1.png" alt="insert ads between posts in WordPress" width="542" height="210" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1.png 542w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1-300x116.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1-60x23.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress-1-150x58.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 542px) 100vw, 542px" /></a></p>\n<p>Inserting the ad between posts with this placement might need some custom adjustments to your layout, especially, if this is a grid with a specific number of elements. Ask your frontend developer or the theme developers for help.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/insert-ads-between-posts-wordpress/">Insert Ads between Posts in WordPress – 3 different methods</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"How to block ads on a specific page?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-block-ads-on-a-specific-page/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 25 Nov 2016 12:37:56 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=39458";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:391:"<p>With Advanced Ads you can exclude ads from specific pages, e.g. to keep your legal pages ad free. The following article shows the two methods for this.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-block-ads-on-a-specific-page/">How to block ads on a specific page?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Joachim";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3548:"<p>With Advanced Ads you can exclude ads from specific posts and pages. E.g., you can keep your ads away from appearing on your contact or privacy policy pages. The following tutorial explains both methods that just need a few clicks.</p>\n<h2>Use display conditions to block individual ads on specific pages</h2>\n<p>With the „Specific Pages“ display condition on the ad edit page you can enter the title or the ID of the site where this specific ad should or in our case shouldn’t appear. That’s all and you can check the results of your settings on your pages afterwards.</p>\n<p>In the following example you can see a setting for an ad that appears on all pages except “Contact” and “Places of interest”.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1.png" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-39568 size-large" title="Block ads on specific pages with Advanced Ads" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1-679x403.png" alt="Disable ads on specific pages" width="679" height="403" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1-679x403.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1-300x178.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1-60x36.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1-150x89.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-specific-pages-1.png 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<p>This method is recommended, if you want to exclude single ads from specific pages, e.g., if you use ads for internal services and you want to disable them on your landing pages.</p>\n<h2>Disable all ads in specific pages</h2>\n<p>If you want to disable all ads on specific posts or pages, it is easier not to exclude them one by one with individual display conditions. In this case, you should look out for the Ad Settings meta box which you can find on the bottom of the edit page of every post and page. You will find a checkbox there which allows you to disable all ads on this page.</p>\n<p>If your are using Advanced Ads Pro, you will find a second option there to disable all ads inside the post content but not from the header, the footer or your sidebar.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-39462 size-full" title="Disable ads inside the content with Advanced Ads Pro" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages.png" alt="disable ads on pages" width="440" height="96" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages.png 440w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages-300x65.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages-60x13.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/disable-ads-on-pages-150x33.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 440px) 100vw, 440px" /></a></p>\n<p>This method is recommended, if you want to keep specific pages with less clicks or legal pages completely ad free.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-block-ads-on-a-specific-page/">How to block ads on a specific page?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"How to add ads on BuddyPress pages?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-buddypress-pages/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 15 Nov 2016 11:15:01 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=38528";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:359:"<p>This tutorial explains how to display ads on BuddyPress pages and inject them into activity streams, group pages or other positions.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-buddypress-pages/">How to add ads on BuddyPress pages?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Hans-Lukas Herse";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4479:"<p>If you have ever tried building a community website using WordPress, you probably already know <a href="https://buddypress.org">BuddyPress</a>. It is a WordPress plugin consisting of multiple components (e.g. groups, private messages, activity streams etc.), which allow you to build your own social network.</p>\n<p>Inserting ads on BuddyPress pages is difficult, because most of them are created dynamically. Automatic injections that work well for normal static pages and posts, are not working as expected on all BuddyPress related pages. Therefore, <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> has placements dedicated exclusively to placing ads on BuddyPress pages.</p>\n<h2>How to display an ad on a BuddyPress page?</h2>\n<p>The placement dedicated to displaying ads on BuddyPress pages is the &#8220;BuddyPress Content&#8221; placement and you can find it in the list of placement types on the placement page.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-38524 size-large" title="BuddyPress Ad Placement" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement-679x200.png" alt="BuddyPress Ad Placement" width="679" height="200" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement-679x200.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement-300x88.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement-60x18.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Placement-150x44.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<p>In order to set up an ad to display using the &#8220;BuddyPress Content&#8221; placement, you only need to select one of the multiple hooks from the &#8220;position&#8221; dropdown menu.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-38523 size-large" title="BuddyPress ad positions" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content-679x213.png" alt="BuddyPress ad position select" width="679" height="213" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content-679x213.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content-300x94.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content-60x19.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/BuddyPress-Content-150x47.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></a></p>\n<p>Hooks listed under &#8220;Activity Entry&#8221; will display the ad in one of multiple positions in the BuddyPress activity streams on the pages &#8220;/activity&#8221;, &#8220;/members/username/&#8221; and &#8220;groups/groupname&#8221;.</p>\n<p>Hooks listed under &#8220;Groups List&#8221; and &#8220;Member List&#8221; will display an ad on the &#8220;/groups&#8221; and &#8220;/members&#8221; pages respectively.</p>\n<p>If you are unsatisfied with the positions provided by the hooks, you can also inject ads using the &#8220;Post Content&#8221; placement, however, this might take a basic understanding of your pages source code.</p>\n<h2>Troubleshooting</h2>\n<blockquote><p>Why is the placement not showing up in my list?</p></blockquote>\n<p>In order to keep the list of placements as short as possible, the placement will only show up if the BuddyPress plugin is activated.</p>\n<blockquote><p>Why are my ads cut on certain pages?</p></blockquote>\n<p>We are merely injecting the ads into the positions provided by BuddyPress, so ads will be cut when they exceed the width of the container they are injected in. Please be sure to choose the correct format for your ads.</p>\n<blockquote><p>Why are my ads not showing up on group pages?</p></blockquote>\n<p>This is due to the fact that pages like &#8220;/groups/name&#8221; or &#8220;/members/name&#8221; are only virtual pages created by BuddyPress and are technically handled as 404 error pages by WordPress. You can fix this issue by disabling the global option &#8220;<label>Disable ads on 404 error pages&#8221; in the Advanced Ads plugin settings. </label></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-buddypress-pages/">How to add ads on BuddyPress pages?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"How to show ads on bbPress pages?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-in-bbpress/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 15 Nov 2016 10:53:58 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=38518";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:345:"<p>This tutorial explains how to add ads to bbPress forum pages and inside the dynamically created threads and posts of such forums.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-in-bbpress/">How to show ads on bbPress pages?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Hans-Lukas Herse";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2888:"<p>Setting up a forum software can be a really tiring endeavor, setting up ads to display on those new forum pages even more. The WordPress plugin <a href="https://bbpress.org">bbPress</a> offers an easy solution to the first problem and provides you with the tools to set up your own forums fast and easy. Advanced Ads provides you with all the tools you need to set up your ads on those pages.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> has two placements to help you setting up ads on forum pages created by bbPress, they are called &#8220;bbPress Static Content&#8221; and &#8220;bbPress Reply Content&#8221;.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-Placements-.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-38520 size-large" title="bbpress Ad Placements" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-Placements--1024x301.png" alt="bbpress Ad Placements" width="980" height="288" /></a></p>\n<h2>How to display an ad on a bbPress page?</h2>\n<p>First of all you need to decide where you want your ad to show up. There are two different placements with multiple hooks to place your ads.</p>\n<p><strong>The bbPress static content placement</strong> provides hooks to inject ads into multiple positions on the /forums, /forums/name or /forums/topic/name pages generated by bbPress.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-static-hooks.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-38522 size-large" title="bbPress static hooks ad Placement" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-static-hooks-1024x355.png" alt="bbpress static hooks ad Placement" width="980" height="340" /></a></p>\n<p><strong>The bbPress reply content placement</strong> provides hooks to inject your ads at the nth reply on /forums/topic/name pages.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-reply-hooks.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-38521 size-large" title="bbPress Ads – reply hooks" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/bbPress-reply-hooks-1024x212.png" alt="bbPress reply hooks" width="980" height="203" /></a></p>\n<p>After choosing the appropriate placement, you only need to select the content you want to display and the hook you want to use from the dropdown menus.</p>\n<p>If you are unsatisfied with the positions provided by the hooks, you can also inject ads using the post content placement. However, this will require a basic understanding of the source code of the page you want to inject the ad into and the element to choose from the available options for the injection.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-in-bbpress/">How to show ads on bbPress pages?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"How to add ads to a masonry layout?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 08:56:58 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=34134";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:336:"<p>Including ads into a masonry grid is tough. It is possible with Advanced Ads though. Find the answer in this tutorial.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/">How to add ads to a masonry layout?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3283:"<p>A masonry layout is a great way to display images in a beautiful grid, even when they have different sizes. It is very common among photography blogs to use a theme which has this feature. You can see some examples on the <a href="http://masonry.desandro.com/">Masonry</a> page.</p>\n<p>However nice it looks, including ads into a masonry grid is not as easy as it might sound. I got asked for a solution a lot and finally had the chance to dig a bit deeper and come up with a way how to solve this with Advanced Ads.</p>\n<h2>Why don’t ads properly display in a masonry grid?</h2>\n<p>Masonry layouts are normally implemented using a JavaScript library. One of the most common libraries for this is <a href="http://masonry.desandro.com/">Masonry by David DeSandro</a>. It is also included in WordPress already and developers only need to activate it.</p>\n<p>The way this and other scripts are working is that they take a set of containers, get their sizes and then reorder them dynamically. All considered elements need to have the same selector. If one of them, like the ad container, does not have this selector – normally in form of a class – it is not considered in the grid and either displays completely outside the grid or is hidden beneath it.</p>\n<h2>How to consider ads in a masonry layout?</h2>\n<p>Based on the explanation above, adding an ad to the layout is actually rather simple.</p>\n<p>You only need to find out which selector is used in the theme to find all elements that need to be considered. In a recent example it was just a list of posts and the class each post container had was <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">recent-post</pre> .</p>\n<p>I then just took this class and added it to the ad container. The option for this can be found on the ad edit screen in the <em>Layout / Output</em> meta box. Simply add the class name to it like on the image below.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-34136" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class.png" alt="container class setting" width="529" height="64" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class.png 529w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-300x36.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-60x7.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-150x18.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 529px) 100vw, 529px" /></p>\n<p>In order to find the correct class you need to ask the theme developer or take a look into the theme’s source code where the masonry script is initialized. For the Masonry script it might look like this:</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">$(''.grid'').masonry({\r\nitemSelector: ''.recent-post'',\r\ncolumnWidth: 200\r\n});</pre><p>\n<p>Adding the ad to the page with the masonry layout is another question. If this is a list of posts, you can use the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placement-post-lists/">Post Lists placement</a> or you can use the PHP function to include it into your theme manually.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/">How to add ads to a masonry layout?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:49:"https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Sep 2016 15:15:35 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=31115";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:313:"<p>This tutorial is about inheriting settings for ads to multiple ads or an ad group.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/">Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3350:"<p>A repeated question in support is how one can use the same conditions for multiple ads at the same time instead of managing them for each ad individually. This is especially useful when using ad groups that need a general layout adjustment or when all ads have the same visitor or display conditions.</p>\n<h2>Using the Ad Group ad type</h2>\n<p>While it is not possible to set visitor or display conditions for a group or placement directly, you can use the <em>Ad Group</em> <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/ad-types/">ad type</a> to accomplish this.</p>\n<p>The setup basically looks like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>you group the inheriting ads into the same ad group</li>\n<li>you create an intermediate ad with the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type</li>\n<li>you assign the group to that ad</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When using the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type, the ad parameters of the intermediate ad show this option:</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-31116" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select.png" alt="ad group select field" width="407" height="50" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select.png 407w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-300x37.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-60x7.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-150x18.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 407px) 100vw, 407px" /></p>\n<p>You can now assign any parameters, display or visitor conditions to the intermediate ad.</p>\n<p>Displaying the intermediate ad works exactly like every other ad. In addition to normal ad output, it will display the group according to the group settings (random, multiple ads, etc.).</p>\n<h2>More scenarios</h2>\n<p>Here are some more ideas for when to use the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type setup.</p>\n<h3>Rotate ad groups</h3>\n<p>With the setup above, you can also rotate ad groups. Just create an intermediate ad for each group and put those into another group.</p>\n<p>You could accomplish a setting like the following easily:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ad Group 1: show 50% of the time; has ad A in it</li>\n<li>Ad Group 2: show 50% of the time; has ads B, C, and D in it which also rotate</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Track all ads together</h3>\n<p>You can set up <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">tracking</a> information for a whole group so that the impressions and clicks for all ads are tracked together. This makes it also easier to set up multiple ads with the same target url.</p>\n<h2>Limitations</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The intermediate ad can not be added to the ad group it is displaying, or else it might create an infinite loop. This should not be possible programmatically, but still good to know.</li>\n<li>Setting different conditions within the individual ads in the group compared to those in the intermediate ad might lead to unexpected behavior.</li>\n<li>Visitor conditions of the individual ads within the selected group only work on cached sites when using <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/cache-busting/">cache-busting</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/">Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"Refresh ads on the same spot";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jul 2016 10:05:16 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=25899";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:288:"<p>How to refresh ads on the same spot without reloading the page.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/">Refresh ads on the same spot</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2546:"<p>In order use an existing placement for multiple ads or to fight ad blindness, you can rotate ads on the same spot during the same page impression.</p>\n<p>In Advanced Ads, this is possible with two features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>refresh on the next page impression using ad groups</li>\n<li>using the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/slider/">Ad Slider add-on</a></li>\n<li>using the refresh option in <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Ad rotation in Advanced Ads Pro</h2>\n<p>With <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a>, you have the additional option of enabling a refresh interval for random and ordered ad groups.</p>\n<p>In order to use that feature, you need to enable the cache-busting module in <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; Pro</em>.</p>\n<p>The option itself can be found in the group&#8217;s options.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-25900" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png" alt="ad refresh interval option" width="441" height="75" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png 441w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-300x51.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-60x10.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-150x26.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 441px) 100vw, 441px" /></a></p>\n<p>Just enable the option and set the time for the refresh in milliseconds.</p>\n<p>The ads will then be reloaded automatically.</p>\n<p>If you are using the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">Tracking add-on</a>, the impression will be counted once per page and only, if the ad really showed up.</p>\n<h2>What else you need to know</h2>\n<p>The number of visible ads at the same time is limited to one, when the ad refresh is enabled.</p>\n<p>Counting impressions for ad refreshes like this is taking some performance, since every call to an ad is loading parts of WordPress. The impact of multiple ad rotations per page set up like above on your server should be monitored by a server admin.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/">Refresh ads on the same spot</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jul 2016 09:47:31 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=25882";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:385:"<p>With Advanced Ads Pro you can run tests based on the position of the ad by rotating the placements against each other.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/">How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4063:"<p>With <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> you can run tests based on the position of the ad. This feature can serve various purposes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>test ads in position A against ads in position B</li>\n<li>rotation different or the same ad to fight ad blindness</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Position tests are running through the placements interface, which you can find unter <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em>.</p>\n<h3>Creating a split test</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> in your site’s dashboard.</li>\n<li>Select a <em>Test weight</em> for the placements you want to test against each other (see below). There is no limit on the number of placements included in a test.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure id="attachment_25884" style="width: 148px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="size-full wp-image-25884" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight.png" alt="test weight setting" width="148" height="47" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight.png 148w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight-60x19.png 60w" sizes="(max-width: 148px) 100vw, 148px" /><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Select the weight for the placement in the test.</figcaption></figure>\n<ol start="3">\n<li>Click on Save New Test.</li>\n<li>The test is now active and should show up in the Placement tests section above all placements.</li>\n<li>After creating a placement test, you can set an expiry date and define an email address to which a short notice is being sent. The expiry date does not remove the test. This option is checked once per day, so the email might be sent with some delay.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure id="attachment_25886" style="width: 746px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-25886" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png" alt="Placement tests overview" width="746" height="155" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png 746w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-300x62.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-679x141.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-60x12.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-150x31.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 746px) 100vw, 746px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Placement tests overview</figcaption></figure>\n<h3>Test weight</h3>\n<p>Test weights work like <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/rotate-ad/">ad rotation weights</a>. E.g., If you set a weight of 2 for Placement A and 4 for Placement B, Placement B will show up twice as often as Placement A.</p>\n<p>Placements show up randomly, i.e. the same placement can show up multiple times in a row before switched to another placement.</p>\n<h3>Evaluating ad tests</h3>\n<p>Unless you are using the test feature to fight ad blindness with random ad positions, you might want to compare the positions with each other.</p>\n<p>In order to do that, you should show different ads for each placement.</p>\n<p>If you run an ad network like AdSense, create different AdSense ad units for the test. You can then use the reports in AdSense to see which ad performed best.</p>\n<p>If you are testing in-house ads, custom code or images, you can use the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">Tracking add-on</a> to track impressions and clicks.</p>\n<h3>What else you need to know</h3>\n<p>In order to test different ads on the same position, you should use an <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/rotate-ad/">ad rotation</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/">How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:10;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"Displaying Ads with Visual Composer";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 16 Jun 2016 08:30:38 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=22134";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:555:"<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is one of the most popular premium page builder for WordPress. No wonder, that I receive many requests on how to use ads, and especially AdSense ad units, directly within the Visual Composer interface. Until now, the simple solution was to use a shortcode from an ad, group or placement created [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/">Displaying Ads with Visual Composer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6126:"<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is one of the most popular premium page builder for WordPress. No wonder, that I receive many requests on how to use ads, and especially AdSense ad units, directly within the Visual Composer interface.</p>\n<p>Until now, the simple solution was to use a shortcode from an ad, group or placement created with Advanced Ads and put it into the text element provided by Visual Composer. However, finding it again among other text elements was a challenge to some users.</p>\n<a class="st-btn large st-btn-blue st-btn-large" href="https://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/ads-for-visual-composer.1.0.zip" target="_self">Download the Visual Composer Add-On</a>\n<h2>Advanced Ads and Visual Composer</h2>\n<p>If you are not a user of Advanced Ads yet, you should take a look at the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/features/">powerful features</a> it provides.</p>\n<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is a premium page builder for WordPress. Instead of writing all your texts and use shortcodes in the editor WordPress provides, Visual Composer replaces that text area with an interface consisting widget-like elements. Those elements can be individually configured, allowing you to build detailed pages with various features. You can even edit pages in the frontend and see how they change live.</p>\n<h2>Visual Composer Ads add-on</h2>\n<p>With the increasing demand, I build an add-on to integrate Advanced Ads and Visual Composer. You can <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/ads-for-visual-composer/">download it for free from wordpress.org</a>.</p>\n<p>Once installed and activated, the add-on you should find three new Visual Composer elements in the editor:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Ad</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Group</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Placement</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There is also a new tab called <em>Ads</em> with these elements.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22135" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png" alt="Visual Composer Ad Elements Tab" width="769" height="149" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png 769w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-300x58.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-679x132.png 679w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-60x12.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-150x29.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 769px) 100vw, 769px" /></a></p>\n<h2>Where to find the ID?</h2>\n<p>When you add and open one of the widgets, you will find an input field for an id of the ad element.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22136" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png" alt="Visual Composer Ads Box" width="338" height="263" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png 338w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-300x233.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-60x47.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-150x117.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 338px) 100vw, 338px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Ad ID</h3>\n<p>Open the ad edit screen and stop the Wizard, if active. You should now see the Ad ID below the ad title.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22137" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png" alt="Ad ID field" width="325" height="80" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png 325w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-300x74.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-60x15.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-150x37.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 325px) 100vw, 325px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Group ID</h3>\n<p>The Group ID is listed in the details column of the ad group list.<a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22138" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png" alt="Ad Group ID field" width="381" height="64" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png 381w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-300x50.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-60x10.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-150x25.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 381px) 100vw, 381px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Placement ID</h3>\n<p>Create a <em>Manual</em> placement. Open the list of placements and click on <em>show usage</em> below the placement’s name. Extract the ID from the id attribute in the shortcode field.</p>\n<p>In the screenshot below, the placement ID is &#8220;theme-header&#8221;.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22139" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png" alt="Ad Placement ID" width="502" height="155" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png 502w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-300x93.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-60x19.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-150x46.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 502px) 100vw, 502px" /></a></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/">Displaying Ads with Visual Composer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:11;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"Displaying alternative content to ad block users";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:75:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 02 May 2016 09:55:59 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Update Notices";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=16891";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:558:"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now. I am going to address this issue as soon [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2336:"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now.</p>\n<p>I am going to address this issue as soon as possible, but in order to do it right, I wanted to ask you for your feedback regarding two important questions.</p>\n<h2>Where to set the alternative content?</h2>\n<p>Advanced Ads has three structural elements: ads, groups and placements. For a better usability, I will only add the option to enter content displayed to ad block users for one of these structural elements. Which one, is still open for discussion. I only believe that it doesn’t make sense on a group level, since many users don’t actually use or need them, but maybe I am wrong.</p>\n<p>Please vote for the level on which you would like to be able to select the content displayed to ad blockers in the following poll:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post''s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<h2>Choosing another “ad” or custom input?</h2>\n<p>The second question is whether there should be a plain input field for the ad blocker content or you want to actually select another “ad” to be displayed, when ad blockers are activated.</p>\n<p>Of course, the alternative ad needs to be undetectable, like custom html code or an image not named “banner” or so, but especially when you want to reuse the alternative ad blocker content, this seems to be a flexible option.</p>\n<p>Please select your favorite option below:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post''s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<p>Please note, that I am only going to accept comments regarding this post. If you have a support question, please <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/support/">contact me through support</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"4";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:4:"href";s:31:"https://wpadvancedads.com/feed/";s:3:"rel";s:4:"self";s:4:"type";s:19:"application/rss+xml";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";a:2:{s:12:"updatePeriod";a:1:{i